# Mobile-First Design Rules

## Core Principle
Always design and develop with mobile devices as the primary target, then progressively enhance for larger screens. The site must look and function perfectly on mobile devices first.

## Mobile-First Development Guidelines

### Responsive Design Strategy
- **Start with mobile styles** (320px and up) as the base
- Use **min-width media queries** to add styles for larger screens
- Test on mobile devices throughout development, not just desktop
- Ensure touch-friendly interface elements (minimum 44px touch targets)

### Tailwind CSS Mobile-First Approach
- Write base styles for mobile (no prefix needed)
- Use responsive prefixes for larger screens: `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`, `2xl:`
- Example: `text-sm md:text-base lg:text-lg` (small text on mobile, larger on desktop)

### Layout Considerations
- **Stack elements vertically** on mobile, arrange horizontally on larger screens
- Use **full-width containers** on mobile with appropriate padding
- Implement **collapsible navigation** for mobile (hamburger menus)
- Ensure **readable font sizes** on mobile (minimum 16px for body text)

### Touch Interface Requirements
- **Minimum touch target size**: 44px Ã— 44px for interactive elements
- **Adequate spacing** between touch targets (minimum 8px)
- **Large, easy-to-tap buttons** for primary actions
- **Swipe gestures** where appropriate (carousels, tabs)

### Performance for Mobile
- **Optimize images** for mobile bandwidth (WebP format, appropriate sizes)
- **Minimize JavaScript** bundle size for faster mobile loading
- **Use lazy loading** for images and components below the fold
- **Prioritize critical CSS** for above-the-fold content

### Mobile-Specific Component Patterns
- **Bottom sheets** instead of modals on mobile
- **Tab navigation** at the bottom of the screen
- **Floating action buttons** for primary actions
- **Pull-to-refresh** functionality where appropriate
- **Infinite scroll** instead of pagination on mobile

### Testing Requirements
- **Test on actual mobile devices**, not just browser dev tools
- **Test on both iOS and Android** devices
- **Test in both portrait and landscape** orientations
- **Test with slow network connections** (3G simulation)
- **Test touch interactions** and gestures

### Breakpoint Strategy
```css
/* Mobile-first breakpoints */
/* Base: 320px+ (mobile) */
/* sm: 640px+ (large mobile/small tablet) */
/* md: 768px+ (tablet) */
/* lg: 1024px+ (desktop) */
/* xl: 1280px+ (large desktop) */
/* 2xl: 1536px+ (extra large desktop) */
```

### Common Mobile Patterns for Snowball

#### Navigation
- **Mobile**: Hamburger menu or bottom tab navigation
- **Desktop**: Horizontal navigation bar

#### Cards and Lists
- **Mobile**: Single column, full-width cards with vertical stacking
- **Desktop**: Multi-column grid layouts

#### Forms
- **Mobile**: Full-width inputs, large buttons, single-column layout
- **Desktop**: Multi-column forms with appropriate spacing

#### Investor/Founder Dashboards
- **Mobile**: Vertical card stack, collapsible sections
- **Desktop**: Multi-column dashboard with sidebars

### Implementation Checklist
- [ ] All new components start with mobile styles
- [ ] Touch targets meet minimum size requirements
- [ ] Text is readable without zooming on mobile
- [ ] Navigation works well with thumb navigation
- [ ] Forms are easy to fill out on mobile
- [ ] Loading states are optimized for mobile networks
- [ ] Images and media are optimized for mobile
- [ ] No horizontal scrolling on any mobile screen size

